  "opinion": "As someone who grew up in a household where my father had a PhD and my mother only completed lower secondary education, I've always been aware of the tension between different educational paths. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've felt firsthand when I've tried to engage with technical fields despite my vocational diploma. It's that quiet anxiety when you're in a room full of people who seem to know more than you do, and you're afraid your performance might confirm a stereotype about your group. For me, this manifests as a constant worry that I'm not 'smart enough' to contribute meaningfully to discussions about engineering or coding, even though I've spent years practicing those skills. We absolutely must address this. In my experience, the best approach isn't about fixing the stereotypes themselves but creating spaces where everyone feels safe to fail without judgment. This means teachers and mentors who actively listen and validate every student's efforts, not just their outcomes. It also means celebrating diverse backgrounds and experiences in STEM fields, so that students from underrepresented groups see themselves reflected in the curriculum. I've noticed that when I've shared my own struggles with stereotype threat, others have been more willing to offer support. It's a slow process, but one that requires patience and empathy. In a world where STEM fields are often seen as the pinnacle of achievement, it's crucial to remember that everyone starts somewhere, and everyone deserves a chance to grow.",
